04849nam a22007215i 9789814951944DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898149519447 a10.1355/97898149519442doi  a(DE-B1597)596889  a(OCoLC)1259588674  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aPOL0290002bisacsh1 aLane, Max, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWidodo’s Employment Creation Law, 2020 :bWhat Its Journey Tells Us about Indonesian Politics /cMax Lane. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (23 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tForeword -- tWidodo’s Employment Creation Law, 2020: What Its Journey Tells Us about Indonesian Politics0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring 2020, the Widodo government introduced a new Bill for parliamentary consideration. This was the Employment Creation Law. It was also known as the Omnibus Law as it introduced amendments to seventy-four other existing laws on a wide range of matters. The Bill provoked considerable controversy, especially provisions reducing protection of labour rights and weakening environmental protection laws. Several provisions introducing further deregulation of a range of activities also attracted criticism. The labour and environmental issues were the basis for a series of street protest mobilizations during the year. These also involved mobilizations where university students participated. The Law was justified by the government in its supplementary material to the legislation as a strategy to attain a specific growth rate in the gross domestic product and arguing that the revisions in the Law were necessary to substantially improve what was described as Ease of Doing Business. Despite the protests and criticism, the law was passed by a big majority in Parliament on 5 October 2020. All member parties of the governing coalition voted for the Bill, and it was signed into law by President Joko Widodo on 2 November 2020. The political journey of this Bill into Law revealed very clearly the homogeneity of the Indonesian political elite, represented by the parliamentary parties, all of whom either supported or acquiesced to the Law. It was also revealed that sustained and mobilized opposition to the Law was basically confined to a section of civil society, with some sections, including important large trade unions, campaigning in only a moderate and constrained way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLegislationxPolitical aspectszIndonesia. 4aSocial Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aLane, Max, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021 Englishz978311075417908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021z9783110753943oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074332640uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981495194440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814951944423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789814951944/original  a978-3-11-074332-6  ISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-074335-7  DG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075417-9  EBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  